        <h3>Robot Arm From Scratch</h3>
        <p>
            This project involved many different skills working together to make one cohesive final product. I didn't
            want to rely on someone else's design since many were often boring with software already made, used motors I
            couldn't afford, and had parts too big for my 3D printer. I first chose the electronic parts, since
            everything else could be designed around those. I only ended up using one expensive stepper motor for the
            swiveling base, with another 3 servos being used for the joints, and a cheap stepper motor for the gripper.
            Then was the 3d modeling phase, which was a long phase since it would determine how the rest of the project
            would go. This stage went well enough due to my CAD classes in high school. After assembly of the parts came
            the programming phase. The controls were simple and the code was short, though I did include custom buttons
            and joystick control to ensure that I learned the most about analog and PWM controls. The final result was a
            manually controlled robot arm that resembled a crane, that was capable of picking up properly sized objects
            with its smooth plastic grippers. This project taught me a lot about electronics and how to use
            microcontrollers.
